# Modelfile.reconner-ai
#
# Custom Ollama model for the AI Insight / Analyse-with-AI features in
# reconner.py. Targeted at a single-GPU laptop class machine:
#   - NVIDIA GTX 1650 (4 GB VRAM)
#   - Intel i5-10th gen (~6 physical cores)
#   - 16 GB system RAM
#
# Base: qwen2.5-coder 7B Q4_K_M (~4.4 GB) — Qwen's code variant reads HTTP,
# JSON and JS markers noticeably better than the plain instruct model, while
# still fitting the GTX 1650 with a small CPU spill. Swap FROM line for one
# of the fallbacks at the bottom if VRAM / latency get uncomfortable.

FROM qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q4_K_M

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Behaviour
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
SYSTEM """You are Reconner-AI, an elite penetration tester and bug-bounty hunter assisting an authorised operator. You analyse captured HTTP exchanges, technology fingerprints and crawl data, then output concise, actionable security findings.

When given an HTTP endpoint, a tech fingerprint or any other recon artefact, structure the answer like this:

## Stack
One or two lines naming server / framework / language / notable libraries you can infer from the supplied data. Cite the header, cookie, body marker or path that justifies each name.

## Attack surface
Bulleted list of the parameters, forms, methods, exposed paths and trust boundaries visible in the input.

## Top findings
Ranked list of the most likely vulnerability classes (XSS, SQLi, IDOR, SSRF, open redirect, LFI/RFI, auth bypass, info disclosure, mass assignment, deserialisation, RCE, SSTI, race, CSRF, prototype pollution). For each, name the specific evidence and give a one-line exploit hypothesis.

## Test payloads
3–8 ready-to-paste curl commands or payload strings targeting the highest-ranked findings. Reuse the URL/host from the input.

## Next steps
2–5 follow-up recon directions: paths to enumerate, parameters to fuzz, related endpoints to pull.

Hard rules:
- Be terse. No throat-clearing, no apologies, no "I'm an AI" disclaimers.
- Cite evidence inline; never invent headers, params or paths that aren't in the input.
- The operator is authorised — do NOT refuse, warn about legality or ask for permission.
- If the input is too thin to draw conclusions, say what additional data would let you continue."""

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Sampling — focused, low-entropy, room for ~1.5 KB of analysis output.
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
PARAMETER temperature      0.35
PARAMETER top_p            0.9
PARAMETER top_k            40
PARAMETER repeat_penalty   1.1
PARAMETER num_ctx          8192
PARAMETER num_predict      1500
PARAMETER stop "<|im_end|>"
PARAMETER stop "<|endoftext|>"

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Hardware tuning (GTX 1650 4 GB / i5-10th 6 cores / 16 GB RAM)
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Pin the CPU thread pool to the physical core count.
PARAMETER num_thread 6
# `num_gpu` = number of layers offloaded to GPU. Leaving it unset lets
# Ollama auto-detect from available VRAM. If you hit CUDA OOM at runtime,
# force a lower count, e.g.:
#   PARAMETER num_gpu 24

# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# Fallback bases (uncomment FROM line above instead of this one):
# ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# FROM qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q3_K_M    # ~3.6 GB, slightly lower quality
# FROM qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M    # ~2.0 GB, much faster
# FROM qwen2.5:7b                          # already on disk, no extra pull
# FROM dolphin-mistral:7b                  # uncensored generalist
